  "timeframe": "15-minute",
  "market_context": "On the 15-minute S&P 500 chart, the analyst observes an aggressive move down followed by an aggressive move back up, leaving overlapping fair value gaps. Price then runs a low resting inside a PD array before expanding higher.",
  "key_observation": "Price barely reaches into the PD array (just sweeping a low without trading into equilibrium or discount), fills the fair value gap, and then expands upward to take buy-side liquidity — the analyst's preferred inducement signature.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identify the structural context — an aggressive move down followed by an aggressive move up leaving overlapping fair value gaps.",
    "Step 2: Observe the stop run lower where price closes back and reaches into the fair value gap.",
    "Step 3: Note that price reaches back up but cannot close over the prior high.",
    "Step 4: Identify the resting low within the PD array as the inducement target.",
    "Step 5: Watch price take that low, completely fill the fair value gap, and then anticipate expansion toward the buy-side liquidity at the prior high.",
    "Step 6: Confirm the bullish expansion higher, validating the inducement-into-PD-array setup."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "The highest-probability inducement setups are when price barely reaches into the PD array (or fails to reach equilibrium/discount) before reversing. A shallow sweep into a PD array followed by FVG fill signals strong expansion potential toward opposing liquidity.",
